    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1978-02-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1978-02-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="138"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d138">
                <head>138. Memorandum From the Assistant to the President for Congressional Liaison
                        (<persName corresp="#p_MF_2">Moore</persName>) to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d138fn1">Source: Carter Library, White House
                        Central Files, Subject File, FO 3–1, Panama Canal, 1. No classification
                        marking. <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> initialed the
                        top-right of the memorandum and wrote: “<persName corresp="#p_NSJ_1"
                            >Nunn</persName> + <persName corresp="#p_HK_1">Hodges</persName> +
                            <persName corresp="#p_BQN_1">Burdick</persName>?”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1978-02-01">February 1, 1978</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Because of the recent accords on Panama, the publicity Senator <persName
                        corresp="#p_BHH_1">Howard Baker</persName> and Senator <persName
                        corresp="#p_BRC_2">Robert Byrd</persName> have received and the deceptive
                    vote in the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, many people have relaxed on the
                    Hill and in the Administration thinking the treaty fight has been won. We are
                    still 9 votes short of the necessary 67, and any combination of 67 votes that we
                    can see is very fragile.</p>
                <p>Some Senators who will vote for final passage will find it very difficult to vote
                    against emotional amendments (flag amendment) which do not mean much to us but
                    would be degrading to Panamanians.</p>
                <p>I am, of course, optimistic that we will pass the treaties. I met with <persName
                        corresp="#p_CA_2">Alan Cranston</persName> last night. <persName
                        corresp="#p_BRG_1">Bob Beckel</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_TR_1">Bob
                        Thomson</persName> are busy going back to see Senators, as am I. Your speech
                        tonight<note n="2" xml:id="d138fn2">A reference to the fireside chat.</note>
                    will create a good mood on the Hill for the next 4 or 5 days while there is a
                    sort of legislative vacuum.</p>
                <p>I have some suggestions for your consideration:</p>
                <pb facs="0404" n="369" xml:id="pg_369"/>
                <p>1. I suggest that we arrange short appointments for you with Senators <persName
                        corresp="#p_FWH_1">Ford</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_ZE_1"
                        >Zorinsky</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_GB_1">Goldwater</persName>, and
                    possibly <persName corresp="#p_HHJ_2">Heinz</persName>.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d138fn3">
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> underlined “<persName
                            corresp="#p_FWH_1">Ford</persName>,” “<persName corresp="#p_ZE_1"
                            >Zorinsky</persName>,” “<persName corresp="#p_GB_1"
                        >Goldwater</persName>,” and “<persName corresp="#p_HHJ_2">Heinz</persName>”
                        and wrote in the right margin: “ok”</note>
                </p>
                <p>2. I suggest that you call Senators <persName corresp="#p_HK_1"
                    >Hodges</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_NSJ_1">Nunn</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_BQN_1">Burdick</persName>.<note n="4" xml:id="d138fn4">
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> wrote in the right margin:
                        “done.”</note>
                </p>
                <p>3. I suggest that <persName corresp="#p_JH_1">Hamilton</persName> call Dr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName> and ask him to talk with
                        <persName corresp="#p_ZE_1">Zorinsky</persName> and any other undecided
                    members he thinks he can help.<note n="5" xml:id="d138fn5">
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> wrote in the right margin: “I
                        will do.”</note>
                </p>
                <p>Former President <persName corresp="#p_FGR_1">Ford</persName> indicated he is
                    willing to help in specific cases. I, also, suggest you consider calling the
                    former President and asking him to talk with Senators <persName
                        corresp="#p_RWV_1">Roth</persName> and Ted Stevens.<note n="6"
                        xml:id="d138fn6">
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> wrote in the right margin: “I
                        will do.”</note>
                </p>
            </div>
